@database SAMREAD
@master "SAMREAD.1"
@remark "manual page source format generated by PolyglotMan v3.2 available at http://polyglotman.sourceforge.net/"
@wordwrap
@tab 8

@node sect0 "Name"
samread, samtype - read a file from a SAMDOS diskette 
@endnode

@node sect1 "Synopsis"
@{b}samread@{ub} [ @{b}-diskfile @{ub}@{i}file@{ui} ] [ @{b}-t@{ub} | @{b}-b@{ub} ] [ @{b}-var@{ub} ] [ @{b}-all@{ub} ]    [ @{b}-dir@{ub}@{i} directory@{ui} ] [ @{b}-file@{ub} ] samdosfile ... @{b}samtype@{ub} [ @{b}-diskfile @{ub}@{i}file@{ui} ] [ @{b}-t@{ub} | @{b}-b@{ub} ] [ @{b}-var@{ub} ] [ @{b}-all@{ub} ]   [ @{b}-dir@{ub}@{i} directory@{ui} ] [ @{b}-file@{ub} ] samdosfile ... 


@endnode

@node sect2 "Description"
@{i}Samread@{ui} copies the specified SAMDOS file or files to the current Unix directory. The filenames may contain wildcard characters.  The use of wildcards or spaces will require the names to be enclosed in quotes to protect them from the shell.  Note: in order to make life complicated, any leading pathname component is treated as the Unix directory in which the file will be placed.  So "samread /tmp/foo" is a request to read the file foo and place it in /tmp/foo, and "samread /bin/*.bin" is a request to read all the files *.bin and place them in the /bin directory.  The MasterDOS directory is specified using the @{b}-dir@{ub}@{i} directory@{ui} flag. @{i}Samtype@{ui} reads the specified SAMDOS file or files and writes them to the standard output.  Note that since this is implemented by the same program as @{i}samread@{ui} any leading pathname components are ignored. Both programs may be used to read files out of a disk image rather than a real floppy by setting the environment variable SAMDISKFILE to the name of the image file or by supplying the @{b}-diskfile @{ub}@{i}file@{ui} flag.  If used this flag must be written first on the command line. It may be abbreviated to @{b}-disk @{ub}@{i}file.@{ui} 

@{i}Samread@{ui} and @{i}samtype@{ui} will allow the following command line options.  One or more of the following may optionally be placed before each file named on the command line: 



À @{b}-t@{ub} @{lindent 3}
Text file transfer. @{i}Samread@{ui} will translate incoming carriage returns into linefeeds, and remove a trailing 255-byte if it is present.  This option applies to all following files until the @{b}-b@{ub} option is encountered. @{lindent 0}

À @{b}-b@{ub} @{lindent 3}
Binary file transfer (the default). @{i}Samread@{ui} will copy each file verbatim.  This option applies to all following files until the @{b}-t@{ub} option is encountered. @{lindent 0}

À @{b}-var@{ub} @{lindent 3}
If any file matched by the following filename is a string variable, then the variable header will be removed from the file to leave just the string's contents.  This option applies only to the filename immediately following. @{lindent 0}

À @{b}-all@{ub} @{lindent 3}
This option causes files to be read from all directories of a MasterDOS disk instead of just the current directory. @{lindent 0}

À @{b}-dir@{ub}@{i} directory@{ui} @{lindent 3}
This option specifies the MasterDOS directory that all the following files are to be read from.  It cancels the @{b}-all@{ub} flag.  See @{i}samtools@{ui}(1) for more information about directories. @{lindent 0}

À @{b}-file@{ub} @{lindent 3}
This option signifies that the next argument is the name of a file to read, even if it has the same name as one of the above options. @{lindent 0}

@{i}Samread@{ui} displays the type information of each file on the standard output.  In the case of a program, this includes the three length values stored in the disk header.  These numbers are required if the program is ever to be given to a Sam. 


@endnode

@node sect3 "See Also"
samtools(1), samwrite(1), samsnap(1) 
@endnode

@node sect4 "Bugs"
There is no option for @{i}samread@{ui} which allows the resulting Unix file to have a name different from that of the SAMDOS file. The @{b}-t@{ub} option is cancelled for all files other than CODE files, or string variables read with the @{b}-var@{ub} option in effect (this cancellation applies only to individual files, not to all files following). 

There is no option for "all the following names refer to string variables". 

The display of file type information is not suppressed for @{i}samtype@{ui} except for CODE or OPENTYPE files, or string variables read with the @{b}-var@{ub} option in effect. 


@endnode
